barngarla_alphabet_page_4_segment_2.plain_text: The traditional people of the Eyre Peninsula are the Barngarla (BARN.ga.rla) (also known as Parnkalla with many other variations having to do with the fact that there was no distinction between P and B) People and this has been supported with documenta on by Revd Clamor Wilhelm Schürmann and Charles Willhelmi, Esq.

barngarla_alphabet_page_4_segment_4.plain_text: Within this group one can also find the Adnyamanthanha, Kuyani, Kaurna, Wirangu, Narungga and Nukunu languages, who are connected through location as neighbours, as well as through marriage and trade. The Thura-Yura language family is within the Pama-Nyungan language family.

barngarla_alphabet_page_4_segment_7.plain_text: However, the language map produced by Wilhelm Schmidt in 1914, and published in 1927 in his book Sprachfamilien und Sprachenkreise der Erde, clearly shows that the Barngarla Language was spoken over the Port Lincoln, Whyalla and Port Augusta area/townships.

barngarla_alphabet_page_4_segment_8.plain_text: This has also been supported by the Federal Court when our Barngarla Native Title Claim Croft vs the State was successful in reaching the first Determination on 22 January 2015 and officially handed back to the Barngarla Community in a special ceremony in Whyalla on 27th June 2018.

barngarla_alphabet_page_4_segment_9.plain_text: Schürmann recorded the Parnkalla Language starting in the early 1840s after he was assigned by the Government to Port Lincoln to engage with and convert the original inhabitants to make relations more amicable between the authorities. He also opened a Native School located just outside of Port Lincoln which only Barngarla People attended.

barngarla_alphabet_page_5_segment_14.plain_text: The Barngarla Community strives to continue to reclaim its ancient language and hopes that with the publication of the Alphabet Book and other educational resources such as the development of the website and the Barngarla language app that is currently free and available to all will lead to more members of the Barngarla Community embedding the language into their daily lives and developing fluent speakers within the younger generations.

barngarla_alphabet_page_5_segment_2.plain_text: What happened (why has it been dormant)

barngarla_alphabet_page_5_segment_3.plain_text: The Barngarla ngawala (language) has been dormant for a long time and the last Barngarla person recorded as speaking it fluently was Senior Barngarla Elder Moonie Davis back in the 1960s which to date is over 50 years ago.

words.word: /* (language) has been dormant for a long time and the last Barngarla person recorded as speaking it fluently was Senior Barngarla Elder Moonie Davis back in the 1960s which to date is over 50 years ago.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_5_segment_4.plain_text: He was also the last known Barngarla person to sing a special song in the Barngarla language that would call the sharks and dolphins to chase the fish into the shallows to the waiting Barngarla people on the shoreline.

words.word: /* He was also the last known Barngarla person to sing a special song in the Barngarla language that would call the sharks and dolphins to chase the fish into the shallows to the waiting Barngarla people on the shoreline.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_5_segment_5.plain_text: The Barngarla language was eroded and became dormant due to the impacts of colonization and government legislation such as the assimilation policy that created the Stolen Generations.

words.word:
/*
The Barngarla language was eroded and became dormant due to the impacts of colonization and government legislation such as the assimilation policy that created the Stolen Generations.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_5_segment_6.plain_text: For the Barngarla People, this would have tragic consequences for future generations which we are now working to rectify by reclaiming the language.

words.word: /* For the Barngarla People, this would have tragic consequences for future generations which we are now working to rectify by reclaiming the language.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_6_segment_2.plain_text: Helping to reclaim the Barngarla Language:

barngarla_alphabet_page_6_segment_3.plain_text: The Barngarla Language Advisory Committee currently consists of 4 people from the Barngarla Community, namely Stephen Atkinson (Chairperson) and committee members Emma Richards, Harold Dare and Jenna Richards.

words.word:
/*
The Barngarla Language Advisory Committee currently consists of 4 people from the Barngarla Community, namely Stephen Atkinson (Chairperson) and committee members Emma Richards, Harold Dare and Jenna Richards.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_6_segment_4.plain_text: Since 2012, we have consistently worked with the revivalist-linguist Professor Ghil'ad Zuckermann since he was engaged by the Barngarla community to seek funding to commence language reclamation workshops.

words.word:
/*
Since 2012, we have consistently worked with the revivalist-linguist Professor Ghil'ad Zuckermann since he was engaged by the Barngarla community to seek funding to commence language reclamation workshops.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_6_segment_5.plain_text: Our role is to provide advice to Ghil'ad and other guests on how to engage with the Barngarla Community respectfully and to ensure that the ancient language of our ancestors remains within the Barngarla Community as a whole.

words.word: /* Our role is to provide advice to Ghil'ad and other guests on how to engage with the Barngarla Community respectfully and to ensure that the ancient language of our ancestors remains within the Barngarla Community as a whole.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_6_segment_6.plain_text: We are currently on our second round of funding and have run regular successful language workshops to interested community members over the past 7 years.

words.word:
/*
We are currently on our second round of funding and have run regular successful language workshops to interested community members over the past 7 years.*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_6_segment_7.plain_text: Our current round of activities involve BLAC, Professor Zuckermann and interested participants from the Barngarla Community working in conjunction with members of the Wardliparringa Unit from SAHMRI on a 5 year research project, which measures the impacts of reclaiming the Barngarla language on the health and wellbeing of participants, as well as continuing to run our regular language workshops and teachers training with the help of the Indigenous Languages & the Arts (ILA).

Our current round of activities involve BLAC, Professor Zuckermann and interested participants from the Barngarla Community working in conjunction with members of the Wardliparringa Unit from SAHMRI on a 5 year research project, which measures the impacts of reclaiming the Barngarla language on the health and wellbeing of participants, as well as continuing to run our regular language workshops and teachers training with the help of the Indigenous Languages & the Arts (ILA).*/

barngarla_alphabet_page_6_segment_8.plain_text: BLAC is the authorised language body of the Barngarla People and is responsible for learning and teaching the Language, and governing and regulating the usage of the language across the board, as well as providing advice and support to those interested parties, other community organisations, services and government departments.

ngarrinyarlboo nhagoodhoo yoora barngarlamadhanga yarda wardarna moondalyabmidhi.

ngarrinyarlboo nhoorralini ngoonidhi gam.lemma: ngarrinyarlboo nhoorralini ngoonidhi gamanggoodhoo ngarrinyarlbooroo yardaroo wardanarriroo.

ngarrinyarlboodningi babmandiga yadharoo.lemma: ngarrinyarlboodningi babmandiga yadharoo ngarrinyarlboo nhooralini yarda boogininya ngarrinyarlbooroo ilgarringgoodhoo, wardanarri gabirri indoo.
